text:
Real World Assets (#RWA) on #Solana and #Ethereum is the next narrative. $1 quadrillion of assets will be tokenized.

RWA is an asset class where an asset is represented by a blockchain token through a legal investment contract between two counterparties.

The regulation of Real-World Assets (RWAs) in the context of crypto involves several government agencies, depending on the specific type of asset and the nature of the regulation required.

Tokenized Securities.

The SEC is responsible for regulating securities, which could include RWAs that are considered securities under U.S. law. Each RWA is individually examined to see if the investment contract linking the token to the asset is a security. 

Tokenized commodities.

The CFTC regulates commodities and derivatives markets, including those that involve RWAs where a token can represent a basket of commodities.

Tokenized bank cash and bank debt.

#Ethereum is the most undervalued ecosystem in the Web 3.0 space

This week I‚Äôve learned that a lot is happening within the Ether ecosystem that social media doesn‚Äôt reflect. 

The gap between fundamental growth and negative price sentiment has never been this big, that I‚Äôm very confident of having a strategy that is heavily skewed towards the Ether ecosystem.

That‚Äôs an interesting aspect of the markets. Retail traders are so far away from reality when it comes to fundamental growth and understanding, that it‚Äôs almost impossible to understand what‚Äôs going on through reading on social media, which means that you‚Äôll be making wrong choices quite often based on just sentiment.

The markets are getting more complex, with more segments, more narratives, and longer-term approaches across the board, as most of the founders I‚Äôve met over the past week don‚Äôt care about short-term hype-based approaches of other founders or projects. The real Web 2.0 founders are eager to build something for the next decade, through which they aim to provide a project that generates revenue through the token, after which it makes it also more possible to track and estimate the value of the project through valuation metrics.

I was relatively concerned before going to https://t.co/7ZuUTygsUJ. Questioning myself whether the altcoins are going to see momentum again, is the Web 3.0 ecosystem still alive or are we getting to the end stages of those coins? But, by being in Brussels, you‚Äôll get to see what‚Äôs really happening and the massive move of founders towards Ethereum to build proper, real companies on top of the Ether blockchain.

It‚Äôs more of Web 2.5, long-term vision, and the phrase ‚Äòaltcoins‚Äô is probably an utterly wrong statement to make. The phrase comes from the altseason period in 2017, which I think won‚Äôt ever happen again. It will be narrative-based hype rallies all along, instead of an entire market moving upwards.

In that case, altcoins I‚Äôd like to refer to are more or less meme coins on Solana and such. The founders I‚Äôve met over the past week are real company builders, rather than altcoin flippers. 

It strengthened my thesis. The Ethereum ETF has enabled such a strong validation for the entire market that the real value of that ETF is going to come after the ETF is listed. However, due to the Ethereum ETF and the BUIDL treasury of BlackRock, the adoption on the builder's side has accelerated massively, through which I think that the Ethereum ecosystem is massively undervalued and the go-to ecosystem to invest in.

text:
A few years ago, #blockchain had the problem of scaling, or better said resolving the blockchain trilemma: create a system which scales, it is secure and it is scalable.

Now, instead of pursuing the purist form of resolving this problem, #Ethereum went towards the rollup centric narrative, which brought in hundreds of problem instead.

Now people are trying to resolve the new problems created by the bad architecture. Now instead of resolving one problem, the ecosystem has to resolve hundreds. There would be no need for complicated bridges, intent based cross L2 operations, chain abstraction with MPC wallets, aggLayers, and more and more. All these words are now thrown at this design as the design brought in more problems than it solved.

And again, throwing "a little" centralisation to resolve scaling, is the wrong way of doing it.

As the number of L2s grow, thus will grow the number of problems, the fragmentation of users and the ecosystem. As that number grows, more people will have to work on new problems risen from this design. Which actually means, not so many people working on applications. This space does not need thousands of L2s, it needs a few ecosystems which can truly scale.

Just take a few steps back and try to imagine a much better ecosystem, put down on paper (without knowing what are the current solutions) what primitive you want, and try to make a completely new design. You will definitely reach SHARDING as the ultimate solution.

Sharding enables even more Sovereign blockspace. Sharding does not limit application/product developers at all. Sharding creates a tightly coupled ecosystem where the network effects are not lost. Sharding scales.

p.s. #EGLDSqueeze

text:
I'm kind of fed up with all the negativity around #Ethereum and Rollups when the whole ecosystem is shipping out of its mind right now. People who look at what we have now and still think Ethereum should have scaled L1 first... are you all out of your minds?

Let me tell you what approximately would have happened if we scaled L1:
- Maybe 50-100 TPS now on L1... wow... I'm sure all the skeptics would have jumped on Ethereum L1 and done all their stuff there.
- Rollups that were previously aligned with Ethereum would most definitely have chosen alternative solutions for DA to meaningfully scale (which is now possible using Ethereum as DA).
- We would not have hundreds of Rollup teams contributing back to the Ethereum and EVM ecosystem.
- Minimal marketing for the Ethereum ecosystem... L2s would just end up doing their own thing, because why should they stay if Ethereum chose to abandon them in the most critical of times?

Ethereum would have essentially pushed the most valuable allies away despite funding a lot of the ZK and rollup research in the past (even 5+ years ago).

We now get so much more back from L2s, and with PeerDAS and full proto-Danksharding on the horizon, there will be no argument left for why those rollups should even think about doing their "own thing" or choosing a different DA. I mean, look at what is happening with $TIA... Ethereum is basically eating their lunch right now.

We now have:
- Multiple Consensus and Execution Client Teams making Ethereum the most decentralized public Blockchain to ever exist by a large margin. AFAIK no other Blockchain even has 2 meaningfully adopted clients... Ethereum has 7 clients with >10% distribution, that's just incredible if you think about it
- Multiple Rollups that are among the most active chains right now
- Both @base and @arbitrum breaking their own records every few days, attracting billions in TVL and millions of users, shipping out of their minds, having meaningful traction, and a growing app ecosystem
- Multiple more theme-focused, Ethereum-aligned L2s like e.g. @Immutable onboarding hundreds of game studios and eventually millions of gamers
- Account abstraction wallets that wouldn't have been easily possible on L1 (at least not so soon) via @Immutable passport or @infinex_app offering sponsored meta transactions
- The cheapest L1 gas fees we‚Äôve probably ever had. Introducing blobs with EIP-4844 made room for more meaningful transactions. At peak times, L2s made up for up to ~30% of the Ethereum blockspace (this most likely still is temporary and also bought us some time to give L1 some love)

I have no doubt in my mind that what Ethereum did has led to the absolute best outcome for the protocol we could have hoped for in the last 3-4 years. 
Of course, L1 could have used some love, but that critique is on such a high level that it feels like we're just coping because the price is not catching up with fundamentals.

If you had told me where Ethereum would be right now 3-4 years ago, I couldn't have imagined a more solid position for it to be in.

Now we can discuss what should be next and that going further down the Rollup path might be a bad idea, or that we should focus on fixing fragmentation, etc., and that delaying this and that in favor of some L1 love is a good idea. I'm totally into that, but please stop with all the coping when we basically just shipped an upgrade that gave @base and other Rollups <1 cent fees ~4 months ago...

#Ethereum and its whole ecosystem is still winning, and nothing can stop it from winning even more, as the whole behemoth that is thousands of ecosystem teams all shipping in parallel is just getting started.
